# API and server action patterns — Drizzle

## Choosing between route handlers and server actions
- **Server actions** (`"use server"`) for form mutations and anything called from a Client Component.
- **Route handlers** (`route.ts`) for webhooks, third-party callbacks, and endpoints consumed externally.

## Server actions
Every server action must:
1. Validate the session (auth provider of your choice — NextAuth, Clerk, custom).
2. Validate and parse input with Zod.
3. Return `{ data: T | null, error: string | null }` — never throw.
4. Scope DB queries to the authenticated user.

```ts
"use server"

import { z } from "zod"
import { eq, and } from "drizzle-orm"
import { auth } from "@/lib/auth"
import { db } from "@/lib/db/client"
import { posts } from "@/lib/db/schema"
import type { Post } from "@/lib/db/types"

const UpdatePostSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string().uuid(),
  title: z.string().min(1).max(200),
  body: z.string().min(1),
})

type UpdatePostResult = { data: Post | null; error: string | null }

export async function updatePost(
  _prevState: UpdatePostResult | null,
  formData: FormData
): Promise<UpdatePostResult> {
  const session = await auth()
  if (!session?.user) return { data: null, error: "Unauthenticated" }

  const parsed = UpdatePostSchema.safeParse(Object.fromEntries(formData))
  if (!parsed.success) {
    return { data: null, error: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors.toString() }
  }

  const [updated] = await db
    .update(posts)
    .set({ title: parsed.data.title, body: parsed.data.body })
    .where(and(eq(posts.id, parsed.data.id), eq(posts.userId, session.user.id)))
    .returning()

  if (!updated) return { data: null, error: "Not found" }
  return { data: updated, error: null }
}
```

The `(_prevState, formData)` signature pairs with React 19's `useActionState`.

## Route handlers
- Return `NextResponse.json({ error })` with the appropriate HTTP status on failure.
- Parse and validate the request body before anything else.
- Authenticate requests that touch user data.
- For webhooks, verify the provider signature before processing.

```ts
// src/app/api/posts/route.ts
import { NextResponse } from "next/server"
import { z } from "zod"
import { auth } from "@/lib/auth"
import { db } from "@/lib/db/client"
import { posts } from "@/lib/db/schema"

const CreatePostSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1),
  body: z.string().min(1),
})

export async function POST(req: Request): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const session = await auth()
  if (!session?.user) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: "Unauthenticated" }, { status: 401 })
  }

  const body: unknown = await req.json()
  const parsed = CreatePostSchema.safeParse(body)
  if (!parsed.success) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: parsed.error.message }, { status: 400 })
  }

  const [created] = await db
    .insert(posts)
    .values({ ...parsed.data, userId: session.user.id })
    .returning()

  return NextResponse.json({ data: created })
}
```

## Webhook pattern

```ts
export async function POST(req: Request): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const body = await req.text()
  const signature = req.headers.get("x-provider-signature") ?? ""
  if (!verifySignature(body, signature, process.env.WEBHOOK_SECRET!)) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: "Invalid signature" }, { status: 400 })
  }
  const event: unknown = JSON.parse(body)
  return NextResponse.json({ received: true })
}
```

## Security checklist
- Authentication before authorization.
- Always filter Drizzle queries by `userId` — Drizzle does **not** have RLS-style automatic scoping.
- Treat all `searchParams`, route params, and request bodies as `unknown`; parse with Zod.
- No secrets in Client Components.
- Rate-limit any public-facing route handler.

## HTTP status codes
- `400` validation failure  ·  `401` unauthenticated  ·  `403` forbidden  ·  `404` not found  ·  `500` unexpected
